Clouds floating above the surface</i>

20
00:01:46,244 --> 00:01:48,177
<i>As the day comes to an end,</i>

21
00:01:48,225 --> 00:01:51,613
<i>and people make their way home,</i>

22
00:01:51,859 --> 00:01:54,418
<i>my own day begins.</i>

23
00:01:54,619 --> 00:01:56,619
Traditional Tonjiru (¥600), Beer (¥600), Sake (¥500), Shochu (¥400)
Max. three drinks per customer
<i> </i>

24
00:01:56,619 --> 00:01:58,866
Traditional Tonjiru (¥600), Beer (¥600), Sake (¥500), Shochu (¥400)
Max. three drinks per customer
<i>My menu is all there.</i>

25
00:01:58,959 --> 00:02:01,519
<i>The possibility of getting
served anything else...</i>

26
00:02:01,961 --> 00:02:04,154
<i>as long as it's possible,</i>

27
00:02:04,229 --> 00:02:06,914
<i>my business model.</i>

28
00:02:07,586 --> 00:02:12,951
<i>I am open from midnight
to seven of the morning after.</i>

29
00:02:13,236 --> 00:02:14,311
<i>People call this...</i>

30
00:02:14,417 --> 00:02:17,244
<i>Midnight Restaurant.</i>

31
00:02:17,711 --> 00:02:19,408
<i>How is business doing?!</i>

32
00:02:19,833 --> 00:02:22,778
<i>Well enough, I'd say.</i>

33
00:02:24,386 --> 00:02:27,378
~ SHINYA SHOKUDO ~
Midnight Restaurant

34
00:02:27,378 --> 00:02:32,588
Episode 1
Red Wiener & Tamagoyaki

35
00:02:43,127 --> 00:02:44,738
By the way...

36
00:02:44,773 --> 00:02:47,603
<i>(*Pork soup with veggies and miso)</i>
Can you make something
else other than traditional Tonjiru*?

37
00:02:47,881 --> 00:02:49,910
Like shogayaki (ginger pork) or something.

38
00:02:50,284 --> 00:02:52,218
Ahh... sure.

39
00:02:52,313 --> 00:02:53,841
Then, I'll go for that.

40
00:02:54,290 --> 00:02:55,555
Coming.

41
00:02:59,290 --> 00:03:00,564
Master.

42
00:03:00,675 --> 00:03:01,810
I'm back.

43
00:03:03,244 --> 00:03:05,462
Hi... You're back home?

44
00:03:05,802 --> 00:03:07,830
How was Macao?

45
00:03:08,036 --> 00:03:10,647
The manager there wanted me
to stay a little longer,

46
00:03:12,137 --> 00:03:14,995
but I already had
the man of my destiny!

47
00:03:17,384 --> 00:03:19,063
And that'd be a Japanese?

48
00:03:19,859 --> 00:03:21,604
It's this Casino dealer.

49
00:03:21,746 --> 00:03:24,669
You know, he's
just great with cards.

50
00:03:25,335 --> 00:03:28,660
Now that I think about it,
your ex was a pianist, right?

51
00:03:28,750 --> 00:03:29,953
For men,

52
00:03:30,076 --> 00:03:32,623
knowing how to use these
is the most important thing.

53
00:03:33,342 --> 00:03:35,817
<i>This kiddo's name is Marilyn.</i>

54
00:03:35,929 --> 00:03:38,439
<i>With what she calls "dance",</i>

55
00:03:38,583 --> 00:03:42,182
<i>she often dazzles my
regulars as a top stripper,</i>

56
00:03:42,290 --> 00:03:44,667
<i>at the New Art in Shinjuku.</i>

57
00:03:45,414 --> 00:03:48,349
Master, just give me some tarako*
and shochu** on top.
<i>(*salted cod roe
**distilled rice liquor)</i>

58
00:03:48,458 --> 00:03:50,191
You want me to roast that tarako?

59
00:03:50,294 --> 00:03:52,123
Yeah... Medium rare.

60
00:03:55,600 --> 00:03:58,157
<i>As our Marilyn seems to fall
head over heels pretty often,</i>

61
00:03:58,272 --> 00:04:00,354
<i>she has the tendency of
taking after her new man's...</i>

62
00:04:00,405 --> 00:04:02,763
<i>every peculiarity and taste.</i>

63
00:04:11,037 --> 00:04:13,034
Can't wait!

64
00:04:45,033 --> 00:04:46,420
Marilyn-chan!

65
00:04:47,033 --> 00:04:48,790
Good showing!

66
00:04:48,905 --> 00:04:50,525
Seems like her new man...

67
00:04:50,634 --> 00:04:54,072
loves medium rare tarako.

68
00:04:56,173 --> 00:04:57,373
Here you go.

69
00:04:57,485 --> 00:04:59,500
Medium rare.

70
00:05:00,490 --> 00:05:02,259
Yummy!

71
00:05:11,193 --> 00:05:14,222
Awesome...

72
00:05:15,498 --> 00:05:19,542
Told you that medium
rare is the best for tarako.

73
00:05:24,047 --> 00:05:25,856
Thanks for that...
'night!

74
00:05:38,912 --> 00:05:40,212
Hi.

75
00:05:51,205 --> 00:05:53,545
Ohh... long time no see.

76
00:05:53,989 --> 00:05:55,519
The usual.

77
00:05:55,966 --> 00:05:57,165
Coming.

78
00:05:58,927 --> 00:06:02,048
<i>Ryu-chan is pretty
famous around here.</i>

79
00:06:03,204 --> 00:06:07,477
<i>Although first impression
sure was terrible, you know?!</i>

80
00:06:08,279 --> 00:06:13,011
<i>Must have been...
not long after I opened.</i>

81
00:06:21,307 --> 00:06:23,554
That's impressive.

82
00:06:24,615 --> 00:06:26,504
If I don't get clients to sign,

83
00:06:26,611 --> 00:06:29,174
the alternative is cleaning toilets, so...

84
00:06:29,263 --> 00:06:31,073
You just get used to it.

85
00:06:32,719 --> 00:06:34,759
Want some fried mackerel?

86
00:06:34,885 --> 00:06:36,598
But, I was...

87
00:06:36,880 --> 00:06:40,452
Just to taste it out,
so it's on the house.

88
00:06:40,728 --> 00:06:42,758
I'm in!

89
00:06:55,638 --> 00:06:58,552
The hell...
Help me out, will you?

90
00:07:00,650 --> 00:07:02,078
This the place?

91
00:07:02,133 --> 00:07:05,130
The one where they cook
you whatever you order?

92
00:07:09,997 --> 00:07:11,991
- You...
- Ahh...

93
00:07:12,071 --> 00:07:13,785
I was just about to
go back to my store...

94
00:07:17,502 --> 00:07:19,622
Oyaji*.
(*middle-aged man)

95
00:07:24,863 --> 00:07:26,572
Escargots.

96
00:07:31,282 --> 00:07:32,991
Can't do.

97
00:07:33,226 --> 00:07:34,590
Then...

98
00:07:34,658 --> 00:07:36,684
Swiftlet nest soup?

99
00:07:37,370 --> 00:07:39,888
I don't have anything that expensive.

100
00:07:40,081 --> 00:07:43,317
What the hell?
What is it you can do?!

101
00:07:50,115 --> 00:07:52,350
Do you have Wiener?

102
00:07:54,278 --> 00:07:56,420
Red Wiener sausage.

103
00:07:59,624 --> 00:08:00,975
Sure do.

104
00:08:01,742 --> 00:08:04,846
Want me to cut
them like an octopus?

105
00:08:54,119 --> 00:08:55,916
How much is it?

106
00:08:58,393 --> 00:09:01,127
If you add the bill from
the guy who left a little earlier...

107
00:09:02,333 --> 00:09:03,372
2,000 yen.

108
00:09:03,402 --> 00:09:04,808
Uh?!

109
00:09:07,566 --> 00:09:10,080
Why does he
need to pay for him?

110
00:09:10,522 --> 00:09:12,252
What's with the prices here?

111
00:09:12,277 --> 00:09:13,741
Keep the change.

112
00:09:18,768 --> 00:09:20,748
Keep the change.

113
00:09:25,614 --> 00:09:27,186
After that day,

114
00:09:27,295 --> 00:09:31,570
Ryu-chan kept showing
up with alarming frequency.

115
00:09:35,362 --> 00:09:36,678
Bon apetit.

116
00:09:45,939 --> 00:09:47,821
Looks tasty.

117
00:09:53,077 --> 00:09:54,997
<i>The curious fella who
just barged in...</i>

118
00:09:55,399 --> 00:09:57,359
<i>walked the straight
road for 48 years,</i>

119
00:09:57,552 --> 00:09:59,292
<i>running a gay bar down the street,</i>

120
00:09:59,408 --> 00:10:01,498
<i>Kosuzu-san.</i>

121
00:10:06,989 --> 00:10:08,929
May I?!

122
00:10:10,100 --> 00:10:12,340
Bon apetit!

123
00:10:20,866 --> 00:10:23,396
This old school taste is just...

124
00:10:29,155 --> 00:10:30,865
Young fella.

125
00:10:32,085 --> 00:10:34,505
I'd feel bad not
giving anything in return,

126
00:10:34,530 --> 00:10:36,760
how about some of my tamagoyaki*?
(*rolled omelette)

127
00:10:36,870 --> 00:10:39,210
I did give it a taste, though.

128
00:10:46,040 --> 00:10:47,310
Thanks.

129
00:10:47,420 --> 00:10:49,090
You're very welcome.

130
00:11:04,748 --> 00:11:06,888
I...

131
00:11:07,146 --> 00:11:12,006
really hate those Yakuza,

132
00:11:15,626 --> 00:11:18,616
but you're different.

133
00:11:19,022 --> 00:11:21,265
<i>(*lit. kettle, pejorative slang for gay men,
originated in the Edo period)</i>
I don't like okama* myself.

134
00:11:21,354 --> 00:11:25,544
Ehh... What are you prattling about?
So stuck up...

135
00:11:26,828 --> 00:11:29,218
Then, what, it's okay?!

136
00:11:34,433 --> 00:11:36,573
You don't see that every day.

137
00:11:36,598 --> 00:11:40,008
Kosuzu-san ending up like that.

138
00:11:44,981 --> 00:11:49,111
<i>~ Shinjuku Golden Street ~</i>

139
00:12:18,043 --> 00:12:18,848
Here you are.

140
00:12:18,873 --> 00:12:20,433
Your tamagoyaki.

141
00:12:21,057 --> 00:12:22,707
Ahh... It's here, it's here!

142
00:12:23,180 --> 00:12:25,920
Ahh... the flavor...

143
00:12:27,238 --> 00:12:28,839
Want a taste?

144
00:12:29,375 --> 00:12:31,362
I'll get diabetes.

145
00:12:31,421 --> 00:12:34,171
I tell you, I eat my
tamagoyaki all nice and salty,

146
00:12:34,635 --> 00:12:37,010
with plenty of dashima (kelp)
soup on top, you know?

147
00:12:37,085 --> 00:12:38,398
You silly...

148
00:12:38,423 --> 00:12:42,293
That's no tamagoyaki,
it's just dashimaki.

149
00:12:47,100 --> 00:12:48,960
So sweet and tasty!

150
00:12:49,142 --> 00:12:50,612
What's so different?

151
00:12:50,785 --> 00:12:53,155
Eat it at a sushi restaurant,
and it's called tamagoyaki.

152
00:12:53,180 --> 00:12:55,630
At a soba (noodle) restaurant,
it's called dashimaki.

153
00:12:55,901 --> 00:12:57,891
I see.

154
00:12:58,350 --> 00:13:01,340
But, Kosuzu-san,
you really love that tamagoyaki.

155
00:13:01,837 --> 00:13:03,685
For your skin, I bet?!

156
00:13:03,901 --> 00:13:05,506
It's not because of that!

157
00:13:05,736 --> 00:13:09,146
Did some past lover of
yours you can't forget like that?

158
00:13:10,584 --> 00:13:12,804
Who knows...

159
00:13:35,149 --> 00:13:36,415
Kosuzu-san.

160
00:13:36,730 --> 00:13:38,930
Want me to roast
you some Wiener?

161
00:13:39,133 --> 00:13:40,453
It's all right.

162
00:13:40,975 --> 00:13:44,172
Ryu-chan already let
me try them out, good stuff.

163
00:13:44,796 --> 00:13:47,966
Ryu-chan said the
same thing about that.

164
00:13:48,630 --> 00:13:50,720
Really?

165
00:13:53,032 --> 00:13:56,882
Thought he'd come by tonight,

166
00:13:57,183 --> 00:13:59,503
but I guess he stood me up again.

167
00:14:01,323 --> 00:14:03,713
Ahh... Master.

168
00:14:04,044 --> 00:14:05,414
You'll excuse me,

169
00:14:05,439 --> 00:14:07,499
but can you wrap this up for me?

170
00:14:07,793 --> 00:14:10,503
The guys at the
bar might be hungry.

171
00:14:10,719 --> 00:14:11,949
Fine with me.

172
00:14:12,087 --> 00:14:13,219
When I have leftovers,

173
00:14:13,328 --> 00:14:15,548
I always give them to a cat
that comes here from time to time.

174
00:14:33,555 --> 00:14:34,935
Here you go.

175
00:14:35,126 --> 00:14:37,704
I made you prepare
more than needed...

176
00:14:37,767 --> 00:14:39,297
Sorry.

177
00:15:05,055 --> 00:15:06,685
As the day comes to an end,

178
00:15:06,854 --> 00:15:09,541
and people are
rushing back home,

179
00:15:09,951 --> 00:15:12,932
they sometimes
get this uneasy feeling,

180
00:15:13,080 --> 00:15:16,210
getting the urge of spending
the night somewhere else.

181
00:15:29,980 --> 00:15:32,975
How should I roast
your tarako, the usual?

182
00:15:33,190 --> 00:15:34,240
Don't roast it.

183
00:15:34,342 --> 00:15:35,932
I'll just have it raw.

184
00:15:37,201 --> 00:15:40,561
Wasn't medium rare
the best for tarako?

185
00:15:41,172 --> 00:15:43,621
The hell does
he know anyway, that man?

186
00:15:44,645 --> 00:15:46,630
You broke up?!

187
00:15:46,677 --> 00:15:48,810
With that medium rare fella.

188
00:15:48,867 --> 00:15:51,897
That mama's boy?!
Forget about it.

189
00:16:00,930 --> 00:16:02,720
- Thanks for that.
- Thanks.

190
00:16:03,306 --> 00:16:05,296
Ohh... Thank you.

191
00:16:07,478 --> 00:16:09,770
Anyone who falls
for men twice as easily...

192
00:16:09,879 --> 00:16:11,888
also grows tired
of them twice as fast.

193
00:16:11,915 --> 00:16:14,975
How are you ever going
to meet a cool man that way?

194
00:16:15,315 --> 00:16:16,755
Shut up, you okama.

195
00:16:16,912 --> 00:16:18,812
Quiet, you kiddo.

196
00:16:19,944 --> 00:16:22,224
Should be tasty
even if it's raw, I guess?!

197
00:16:23,810 --> 00:16:25,340
You even fall for a Yakuza now...

198
00:16:25,365 --> 00:16:28,020
You're losing your charm, Sis.

199
00:16:28,045 --> 00:16:29,590
It's not that.

200
00:16:30,270 --> 00:16:31,520
Marilyn.

201
00:16:31,570 --> 00:16:34,960
Falling in love,
dying for love or whatever...

202
00:16:35,564 --> 00:16:38,134
I already graduated from that
school of thought a long time ago.

203
00:16:39,625 --> 00:16:41,730
Maybe because you lasted
a lot longer than you deserved,

204
00:16:41,755 --> 00:16:44,005
you had more
time to experience?!

205
00:16:44,035 --> 00:16:47,193
But if you fall for a Yakuza,
he'll probably run you dry?

206
00:16:47,235 --> 00:16:49,302
Is Ryu-chan not coming?

207
00:16:49,708 --> 00:16:52,428
He's probably busy
blackmailing someone?

208
00:16:53,173 --> 00:16:56,533
That man is a righteous fella.

209
00:16:56,558 --> 00:16:58,648
I can feel it.

210
00:16:59,589 --> 00:17:02,716
<i>You know what they say,
can't judge a book by its cover.</i>

211
00:17:02,741 --> 00:17:05,691
Still, isn't he a little too tall?

212
00:17:11,214 --> 00:17:13,532
Yes, my apologies.

213
00:17:13,557 --> 00:17:15,405
Right... About that,

214
00:17:15,430 --> 00:17:18,050
we'll do whatever is possible...

215
00:17:19,496 --> 00:17:21,196
Kenzaki!

216
00:17:42,617 --> 00:17:44,781
It hurts...

217
00:17:44,980 --> 00:17:46,070
Gen.

218
00:17:46,160 --> 00:17:48,550
- Are you okay?
- It hurts so bad!

219
00:17:48,650 --> 00:17:51,030
It hurts...

220
00:18:02,594 --> 00:18:04,047
Aneki (Yakuza's "big brother")!

221
00:18:04,133 --> 00:18:05,690
Aneki!
Aneki!

222
00:18:06,066 --> 00:18:07,127
Aneki!

223
00:18:09,517 --> 00:18:11,175
You bastard!

224
00:18:11,200 --> 00:18:13,460
Stop there!

225
00:18:13,760 --> 00:18:16,670
~ Imashiro gang Kingpin stabbed ~

226
00:18:17,360 --> 00:18:18,530
Is gang warfare back?

227
00:18:18,610 --> 00:18:20,840
The Victim - Kenzaki Ryu

228
00:18:30,094 --> 00:18:31,325
Thankfully,

229
00:18:31,532 --> 00:18:33,946
he wasn't seriously injured,

230
00:18:34,374 --> 00:18:38,094
but Ryu-chan will have to spend
some time at the hospital.

231
00:18:41,102 --> 00:18:42,690
Master...

232
00:18:42,956 --> 00:18:45,786
I have a favor to ask...

233
00:18:53,811 --> 00:18:56,561
First layer!

234
00:19:00,957 --> 00:19:03,347
Second!

235
00:19:04,766 --> 00:19:06,249
And...

236
00:19:06,274 --> 00:19:08,994
third... one!

237
00:19:10,118 --> 00:19:11,551
It's a buffet, all right.

238
00:19:11,576 --> 00:19:14,336
I asked Master to make it for me.

239
00:19:16,507 --> 00:19:18,297
Go ahead.

240
00:19:28,030 --> 00:19:30,399
So I guess red
wiener and tamagoyaki...

241
00:19:30,424 --> 00:19:34,060
are the two big stars of any bento*
(*home-packed meal)?

242
00:19:34,982 --> 00:19:38,652
Is there any memory
those wieners bring back?

243
00:19:53,777 --> 00:19:56,660
Everyone keeps some
kind of special memory...

244
00:19:57,152 --> 00:19:59,752
buried deep down their soul.

245
00:20:03,877 --> 00:20:05,600
Still,

246
00:20:05,908 --> 00:20:08,684
one day, I want
to tell you everything...

247
00:20:08,709 --> 00:20:12,129
about the memories that
tamagoyaki brings back to mind.

248
00:20:16,198 --> 00:20:19,758
It's a relief
they didn't kill you.

249
00:20:20,232 --> 00:20:22,822
Without you...

250
00:20:23,665 --> 00:20:25,565
I'd just...

251
00:20:29,028 --> 00:20:31,018
I know!

252
00:21:08,003 --> 00:21:10,713
Isn't it time to go?

253
00:21:11,276 --> 00:21:13,936
Got work to do.

254
00:21:14,857 --> 00:21:16,911
This world of ours...

255
00:21:16,936 --> 00:21:21,136
is made of ebbs and flows,
like the Sumida River.

256
00:21:22,350 --> 00:21:24,750
Don't belittle life.

257
00:21:51,098 --> 00:21:53,998
You have katsuobushi*?
(*dried fish scrapings)

258
00:21:54,595 --> 00:21:56,875
I do have it, but...

259
00:21:57,812 --> 00:22:02,302
I wanted some on top of warm rice,
sprinkled with soy sauce.

260
00:22:04,250 --> 00:22:07,250
You mean nekomanma (cat rice)?

261
00:22:07,997 --> 00:22:09,393
<i>That was...</i>

262
00:22:09,418 --> 00:22:12,888
<i>the first time she
came to my restaurant.</i>

263
00:22:14,726 --> 00:22:18,056
<i>~ To be Continued ~</i>

264
00:22:21,293 --> 00:22:23,203
Everyone!

265
00:22:23,688 --> 00:22:26,052
Fried eggs might
be simple to make,

266
00:22:26,077 --> 00:22:29,177
but tamagoyaki is a
tad more difficult, right?

267
00:22:29,594 --> 00:22:32,203
Still, don't just give up on it.

268
00:22:32,228 --> 00:22:34,578
Shall we give
this challenge a try?

269
00:22:37,632 --> 00:22:40,988
Make them scramble
over the frying pan,

270
00:22:41,013 --> 00:22:43,563
and they'll grill gently.

271
00:22:45,975 --> 00:22:49,553
Fold it sideways just like this,

272
00:22:49,578 --> 00:22:51,505
push it aside,

273
00:22:51,530 --> 00:22:53,980
and pour over.

274
00:22:54,538 --> 00:22:57,558
When it starts making
bubbles, break them.

275
00:23:02,314 --> 00:23:04,504
So, see you again!

276
00:23:04,529 --> 00:23:06,249
Good night!

